headline: Strong Bank Earnings Push S&P 500 Higher
summary: Morgan Stanley  shares jumped 4.7% after better-than-expected results, while  Bank of America  similarly vaulted 4.4% higher.  Perhaps just as important for Wall Street, America’s most powerful financiers said U.S. consumers and businesses are continuing to spend despite concerns the Trump administration’s agenda could slow the economy, boost inflation, or both.  Morgan Stanley Chief Executive  Ted Pick  described the backdrop in an earnings call as one in which “macro uncertainty and enormous opportunity uncomfortably coexist.”

headline: PNC Offers Mixed Picture on Consumer, Business Credit
summary: PNC Financial Services set aside more money within its retail banking unit in case customers fall behind on loan payments, but decreased its provision for credit losses within its corporate and institutional banking unit.  The retail banking unit’s provision for credit losses was $126 million for the third quarter, an increase of $43 million from the second quarter and up $15 million from the third quarter of 2024.  The corporate and institutional banking unit’s provision for credit losses came in at just $44 million for the third quarter.

headline: PNC Financial Stock Falls Even as Earnings Beat Estimates
summary: PNC Financial Services reported third-quarter earnings per share of $4.35 on revenue of $5.9 billion, exceeding Wall Street expectations of earnings of $4.05 on revenue of $5.8 billion.  PNC benefited during the quarter from higher net interest income, which is the difference between what a bank earns on interest-bearing assets and pays in interest on deposits.  Last month, PNC said it would acquire FirstBank, a Lakewood, Colo.-based bank, for $4.1 billion.
